We recommended that the Municipal Mayor direct:
the Municipal Engineer to expedite the extraction of data as to the complete description and cost segregation of road components for road projects, and thereafter furnish such information to the Municipal Accountant and Property Officer;
the Municipal Assessor to furnish the GSO of documents related to those newly acquired parcels of land during CY 2021;
the Municipal Accountant to maintain complete ledger cards of the PPEs, reconcile the same with the property cards of the GSO-Designate and disclose in the Notes to Financial Statements the total road network system as prescribed in Annex B of COA Circular 2015-008;
the GSO-Designate to maintain complete property records, conduct annual physical inventory count of all properties of the Municipality, including infrastructure assets, as well as, prepare and submit the complete RPCPPE to the Auditor within the prescribed period; and
the Property and Accounting Units to investigate, correct, adjust and record the unreconciled PPE balances between the books and inventory report and undertake the procedural guidelines enumerated in COA Circular No. 2020-006 for the one-time cleansing of PPE account balances to come up with more reliable account balances to be presented in the financial statements.
We also recommended that the Municipal Mayor instruct the Disposal Committee to expedite the disposal of unserviceable properties to free up storage spaces, prevent further deterioration of PPE and generate additional income from sale.

We recommended that the Management direct the:
Municipal Treasurer to:
Strictly implement the provisions of the Municipal Revenue Code in order to correct the assessment and collection of business taxes that will accrue to the Municipality;
Conduct verification on transactions recorded by the Municipality and compare it to the amount of sales declared on renewal of business permits.
Enforce collection of the underdeclared sales noted with corresponding interest, surcharges, and penalties.
Conduct regular inspection and verification of financial records of the business establishments to ensure that the correct gross receipts will be declared by the taxpayer;
Set up or  institutionalize  a  standard  computation  that  could arrive in a more realistic basis of business taxes in the absence of the required audited financial statements or BIR returns or sworn declaration of the gross receipts; and
Maintain periodic reviews together with concerned officials to ascertain whether collection targets are attained. Those reasons for the shortfall in collections should be analyzed and alternative methods  or  procedures  be  undertaken  to  avoid the incurrence of shortfall in the future;
Business and Permits Licensing Officer (MBPLO) to:
Refrain from  accepting  application  for  the  renewal  of business permits that are  not  based  on  the  documentary requirements like the audited financial statements or BIR returns or sworn declaration particularly when the taxpayer submit the prior year’s gross receipts in rounded figures;
Require submission of  complete  documentation  of   the financial records from taxpayers for the correct assessment of taxes; and
Maintain and use an individual ledger or index card for each business establishment in recording their tax payment.

We have recommended the Municipal Mayor direct:

the Municipal Engineer to furnish copy of complete description and cost segregation of road components for road projects as well as Government Report on Programs/Projects/ Activities to Municipal Accountant and Property Officer;

the Municipal Assessor to furnish the GSO of documents related to land;


the Municipal Accountant to:            i) maintain complete ledger cards of the PPEs; 

ii) reconcile the same with the property cards of the GSO-Designate;



iii) derecognize the overstated Building account by P1M; and 


iv) disclose in the Notes to Financial Statements the total road network system as prescribed in Annex B of COA Circular No. 2015-008;

the GSO-Designate to:  i) complete the property records and PAR; 


ii) conduct annual physical inventory count of all properties of the Municipality, including infrastructure assets; and 

iii) prepare and submit the RPCPPE to the Auditor within the prescribed period; and

the Property and Accounting Units to investigate, correct, adjust and record the unreconciled PPE balances between the books and inventory report and undertake the procedural guidelines enumerated in COA Circular No. 2020-006 for the one-time cleansing of PPE account balances to come up with more reliable account balances to be presented in the financial statements.  

Also, to prepare and maintain required records and documents under COA Circular No. 2015-008 for fair presentation of the Local Road Network account in the financial statements.

We have recommended that the Municipal Mayor, through the Solid Waste Management Board to:

promote Solid Waste Management Awareness through proactive Information and Education Campaign  (IEC) such as seminars/trainings/ forums, informative and visually striking related signages posted in conspicuous areas and use of social media in information dissemination, in coordination with the Barangay Solid Waste Management Committees and academic institutions;

adopt guidelines that will ensure waste segregation at source such as non-collection of garbage if not segregated as to recyclable or not, information dissemination of proper use of MRF and benefits of waste segregation, and establishment of additional MRFs to accommodate all recyclable wastes of the locality;

expand the collection areas of the garbage collection to include all the barangays of the Municipality; and





fast-track the establishment of the engineered sanitary landfill to comply with Section 17 of RA no. 9003.

We have recommended that the Municipal Mayor direct:

the LEE Manager to:  i) formulate a plan that will increase the success rate of the LEE in terms of profitability and financial   standing;   ii) employ marketing strategies to extend the reach of its services, especially in the barangays where it is intended to operate; and iii) coordinate with the Municipal Accountant in checking regularly the loan profile related to the AWSS such that details and information will be readily available;

the Municipal Accountant:  i) request loan and payment records from the MDFO/debtor’s office; and


ii) record all transactions related to AWSS to its own books to reflect its actual performance in the financial statements;

the erring officers to pay the fines and penalties incurred due to the non-payment of the loan who should have been responsible of monitoring the loan, and coordinating with the debtor; and

the Team created as per EO No. 14:  i) to convene and assess regularly the performance of the AWSS; and ii) assist the LEE Manager in its operations, particularly increasing the AWSS concessionaires/ subscribers and revenues while decreasing the subsidy given the LGU so as to fully embody its being a Local Economic Enterprise.

We have recommended that the Local Chief Executive (LCE) direct the:

Municipal Treasurer to exert more effort in the collection/liquidation of the long outstanding loan assistance to NGOs; and assist the Aringay Tobacco Growers Association in devising strategies on how to collect the loans of its delinquent member-borrowers;

Municipal Agriculturist to assist the Organic Agri-Services Network of Aringay in devising strategies to operationalize the farm tractor so that income could be generated that will help them pay their loan from the Municipality.

