We have recommended the Local Chief Executive (LCE) direct the concerned officials to:

authorize cash advances with a) legally specific purpose, b) have complete supporting documentation such as approved Obligation Requests from the Municipal Budget Officer and other documents peculiar to the transaction, and c) the accountable officer requesting has settled his/her previous cash advances;

liquidate the outstanding cash advances amounting to P239,198.94;

liquidate the cash advance within the prescribed period or as soon as the purpose for which it was given has been served; 


use Petty Cash Fund for payment of authorized petty or miscellaneous expenses which cannot be conveniently paid through checks, otherwise use checks directly payable to the supplier or creditor; and


prepare necessary adjusting entries to reflect fair presentation of affected accounts.

We have recommended the Management the following:

Cease the practice of transferring cash advance from one Accountable Officer to another;




Reflect to the liquidation report the actual disbursements made to cash advance by attaching the appropriate supporting documents;



Comply with RA No. 9184 on the procurement of goods; 

Pay directly to suppliers through checks and withhold applicable taxes due to the national government; 

Apply COA Circular No. 94-013 in the implementation and reporting of program/projects, if necessary; and

Supporting documents of transactions should reflect the truthful narration of facts in order to prevent sanctions set forth in Article 171 of Revised Penal Code.

We have recommended the Local Chief Executive:

direct the Bids and Awards Committee to thoroughly conduct the bid post-qualification procedures in order to ensure that the suppliers or contractors have the ability to deliver and/or perform their part of the contract;

direct End-User Departments to conduct necessary analyses like the cost-benefit analysis before requesting for the purchase of products, so that risks could be minimized while benefits be maximized;

direct the Project-in-Charge to closely monitor their assigned projects, especially old and continuing ones.  In connection to this, the Project-in-Charge should also determine delays, if any, so that appropriate actions for similar situations may be done promptly;

impose liquidated damages from the supplier for the undelivered amount of contract of P299,000.00. Furthermore, as a result of the liquidated damages exceeding 10% of the total contract price, the Local Chief Executive may rescind the contract; and


recommend blacklisting of the said supplier/ contractor

We have recommended the Municipal Treasurer the following:

Continue to demand settlement of tax liabilities from the identified taxpayers;

Adopt corresponding strategies to address the specific concerns of the taxpayers on non-payment of real property tax; and coordinate with the Provincial Treasury Office and avail of the administrative and legal remedies provided by law to enforce collection of the delinquent real property taxes.

We have recommended that the Local Chief Executive (LCE):
Appoint or designate a General Services Officer as mandated by the Local Government Code, otherwise the Municipal Treasurer will be responsible on the custody of and be accountable for all properties, real or personal, owned by the local government unit and those acquired by the Municipality in the form of donation, reparation, assistance and counterpart of joint projects, among others as included in by Section 114 of the Manual on New Government Accounting System for Local Government Units;
Require the General Services Officer / Municipal Treasurer to complete the list of PPEs in his records including information required to be contained in the Property Cards and  the Municipal Accountant to complete his PPE ledgers cards;
Create an Inventory Committee and direct the same to conduct complete inventory of all the PPEs of the LGUs; and
Require the Municipal Treasurer, Accountant and Assessor to reconcile their records, so that discrepancies may be investigated on a timely basis.

Based on the foregoing observations, we have recommended the Local Chief Executive (LCE) direct the concerned officials to:
Authorize cash advances with a) legally specific purpose, b) have complete supporting documentation such as approved Obligation Requests from the Municipal Budget Officer and other documents peculiar to the transaction, and c) the accountable officer requesting has settled his/her previous cash advances;
Liquidate the outstanding cash advances amounting to P239,198.94;
Liquidate the cash advance within the prescribed period or as soon as the purpose for which it was given has been served;
Use Petty Cash Fund for payment of authorized petty or miscellaneous expenses which cannot be conveniently paid through checks, otherwise use checks directly payable to the supplier or creditor; and
Prepare necessary adjusting entries to reflect fair presentation of affected accounts.

Strictly enforce waste segregation at source  in order to achieve the primary objective to protect the environment and public health from substantial, present, and potential hazard of solid wastes as well as to secure continuation of MOA with Municipality of Agoo;
Promote Solid Waste Management Awareness through, proactive Information and Education Campaigns (IEC) in coordination with the Barangay Solid Waste Management Committees and academic institutions i.e. seminars/trainings/forums, informative and visually striking related signages posted in conspicuous areas, use of social media in information dissemination, etc.; and
Address the issues on the establishment of the engineered sanitary landfill.

